ntal sustainability, and provide both a broad view of university engagement and a detailed examination of various projects. As part of this series in association with the Place and Social Capital and Learning (PASCAL) International Observatory, the three key PASCAL themes of place management, lifelong learning and the development of social capital are considered throughout the book.While universities have historically generated knowledge outside of specific local contexts, this book argues that it is particularly important for them to engage with the local community and to consider diverse perspectives and assets when looking at issues within an ecological context. The chapters in this volume provide new perspectives and frames of reference for transforming universities by engaging in the development of resilient communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity and collegexUnited States. 0aCommunity and collegezUnited States. 0aSustainabilityxUnited States. 0aSustainability. 0aUniversities and collegesxEnvironmental aspectsxUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegesxEnvironmental aspectszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Administration / General.2bisacsh  aecology.  aenvironmental sustainability.  ahigher education.  aregional engagement.  auniversity engagement.1 aBiao, Idowu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChawawa, Morgan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClover, Darlene E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarlick, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInman, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInman, Patricia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLammers, Roberta, econtributo